FBIS3-31565 "dreeu035_i_94016" FBIS-EEU-94-035 Document Type:Daily Report 22 Feb 1994 BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA Vice President Calls UN Ultimatum `Mistake' LD2102214794 Paris France-2 Television Network in French 1900 GMT 21 Feb 94 LD2102214794 Paris France-2 Television Network Language: French Article Type:BFN [Excerpts] Sarajevo was blessed with another calm day. [passage omitted] Stephane Manier and Marcel Martin report: [Begin recording] [Manier] [passage omitted] Whereas the man on the streets keeps turning his bitterness over without really realizing that he can now think about it at his leisure, politicians look at the situation with more distance: [Ejup Ganic, Bosnian vice president, in English with French voiceover] I, for one, did not think that at 0100 last night, something would necessarily happen. In the case of an ultimatum, you never know when reactions start effectively. However, I am worried when I see that there is still quite a lot of uncontrolled artillery. It is up to NATO to defend its own credibility. We complied and cooperated. The Serbs did not. I think that we are now pressing for the Serbs to cooperate, but I do believe that the UN made a mistake when it negotiated the ultimatum with the Serbs. [end recording]
